THE RISK (context, do not rewrite): perturbation [{"nodeId":"tamBase","op":"set","value":280,"note":"Recentre on the primary scope-down chain after discarding the contaminated €495M ceiling; effective distribution 240–320"}], likelihood 0.52, category model-structure

FIELDS TO REWRITE:
{
 "title": "The €495M cross-check ceiling grows at 21.23% CAGR — it is measuring the substitute architecture, and the band's upside is a mirage",
 "narrative": "The high end of tamBase's band (€520M, worth +€3.3M YAM at the band edge) rests on one calculation: BIS's €2.45B Europe 'PDUs + PSUs' figure × an unsourced ~55% PDU share. But that BIS category grows at 21.23% CAGR — a rate no mature rack-PDU market exhibits (every rack-PDU-only source says 5.4–9.8%). A 21% growth rate in a 'PDUs and PSUs' category is the signature of OCP power shelves and rack-level DC power supplies — precisely the substitute architecture the model's boundary excludes. The ceiling isn't a generous estimate of the venture's market; it's a measurement of the thing eating the venture's market. If the board sizes hiring, inventory, or the raise against the band midpoint on the theory that upside and downside are symmetric, they are capitalizing a number that contains the competitor architecture's growth.",
 "mechanism": [
  {
   "step": "trigger",
   "text": "The BIS/R&M Europe 'PDUs + PSUs' base ($2.45B → $20.05B, 21.23% CAGR) used for the crossCheck ceiling grows 2–4x faster than every rack-PDU-only estimate (5.4–9.8% across five publishers) — a growth signature inconsistent with the rack-PDU scope it is being used to validate",
   "refs": [
    "digest:tam-base#c2",
    "digest:tam-base#c3",
    "digest:tam-global-crosscheck#c7",
    "digest:tam-global-crosscheck#c6"
   ]
  },
  {
   "step": "propagation",
   "text": "The excess growth must sit in the PSU/DC-power-shelf portion of the category — the excluded substitute — and the '~55% PDU share' applied to strip it out is unsourced, so the €495M ceiling inherits an unknown fraction of substitute-architecture revenue; MarketsAndMarkets' 19.5% CAGR for its broader rack+floor PDU scope shows the same contamination pattern",
   "refs": [
    "ledger:tamBase",
    "digest:tam-base#c4",
    "digest:tam-base#c5"
   ]
  },
  {
   "step": "model-impact",
   "text": "tamBase's true uncertainty is asymmetric: the primary chain supports €240–320, while the 520 high edge is scope-contaminated — any planning premised on the band's symmetric upside (the +€200M dTam edge in the affordances) overstates the venture's realistic ceiling",
   "refs": [
    "ledger:tamBase"
   ]
  }
 ],
 "whyMissable": "Cross-checks exist to add confidence, and this one is dutifully labeled 'broader scope used as the cross-check ceiling' — the caveat is in the ledger. What the caveat hides is that the broader scope isn't just broader, it's adversarial: its growth is the substitute's growth. A wide band reads as honest uncertainty; nobody asks whether one edge of the band is made of a different market.",
 "falsifier": "BIS/R&M report segmentation showing the PDU-only sub-segment at ≥55% of the category AND growing ≤10% CAGR — which would confirm the ceiling as a legitimate rack-PDU reading.",
 "likelihoodRationale": "The CAGR incompatibility is arithmetic and visible in the cited excerpts (21.23% vs 5.4–9.8% for the same nominal product), and the 55% PDU share is admitted as unsourced; the only uncertainty is how much of the excess growth is PSU/shelf revenue vs report optimism. [evidence revision: Evidence firmly confirms the arithmetic (21.23% CAGR, €2.45B base) and the interpretive premise that the category bundles DC-power/PSU substitute architecture (VRMs, AC/DC and DC/DC converters) growing well above rack-PDU-only rates. This strengthens the trigger and propagation steps. However, the load-bearing quantitative claim — that the unsourced ~55% PDU share materially over-captures substitute revenue — remains unverified because no segmentation breakdown surfaced; OCP power supply itself grows at only 12.4%, leaving open how much of the 21.23% is report optimism versus genuine substitute contamination. Modest upward revision from 0.45 to 0.52.]"
}

